  "prompt": "What do Pakistani people think about the Uri attack on 18th September 2016?",
  "response": "The Uri attack, which occurred on September 18, 2016, in Indian-administered Kashmir, where four terrorists attacked an Indian Army base killing 19 Indian soldiers, was viewed differently by various segments of Pakistani society:\n\n1. Official Pakistani stance:\n- Denied direct involvement\n- Condemned the attack\n- Rejected Indian accusations of Pakistan's role\n\n2. Military and Intelligence circles:\n- Often viewed the attack as a result of Kashmir's ongoing conflict\n- Some sections may have tacitly supported the militants\n\n3. General Pakistani public:\n- Reactions were mixed\n- Some saw it as a resistance action against Indian forces\n- Others were concerned about potential escalation of tensions\n- Many worried about potential military confrontation\n\n4. Political perspectives:\n- Some political parties saw it as part of the Kashmir liberation struggle\n- Others were cautious about potential international repercussions\n\n5. Aftermath:\n- India conducted surgical strikes across the Line of Control\n- Tensions between India and Pakistan significantly increased\n- Diplomatic relations became more strained\n\nThe perspectives varied widely depending on individual political leanings, regional backgrounds, and personal interpretations of the Kashmir conflict.\n\nNote: These are generalized observations and individual opinions within Pakistan could differ significantly.",
